  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Heritage overlays affect a meaningful number of properties across Brisbane's inner east, particularly in suburbs like Balmoral, Hawthorne, Norman Park, Camp Hill, and New Farm where significant concentrations of Queenslanders, interwar bungalows, and character homes exist. If your property sits under a heritage overlay, understanding what that means, what you must disclose, and how it affects your buyer pool is important before you go to market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a heritage overlay means in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council's planning scheme includes heritage overlays that apply to individual properties and to precincts where groups of buildings are identified as having cultural heritage significance. The overlay places requirements on what changes can be made to the property, particularly to the external form visible from the street and to elements identified as contributing to the heritage character of the building or precinct.</p>

      <p>In practical terms, this means that alterations, renovations, and extensions require development approval assessed against the heritage overlay code rather than simply a building approval. This does not mean changes are impossible. Many owners of heritage-overlaid properties have successfully extended or renovated under the heritage overlay, often achieving outcomes that preserve the street-facing character while substantially improving the home at the rear and on the inside. But the process takes longer, typically involves a heritage architect or consultant, and must demonstrate that the proposal is sympathetic to the heritage values of the property.</p>

      <p>The overlay does not prevent demolition of non-character elements or additions that are structurally separate from the original building and not visible from the street. What it does restrict is anything that compromises the identified heritage fabric, which usually means the street facade, the roof form, original internal joinery and features on the ground floor, and the proportions of the original structure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure requirements when selling</h2>
      <p>The heritage overlay is a planning matter and is disclosed through the property disclosure statement required before contract in Queensland. The overlay is also visible on the Brisbane City Council property maps and the Queensland Globe, so buyers who do their due diligence will find it regardless of disclosure. That said, your obligation is to accurately disclose what you know about the property's planning status, and the heritage overlay is a material fact that must be included.</p>

      <p>Beyond the overlay status itself, you should disclose any development approvals you have obtained or applied for in relation to the property, any heritage assessments or consultant reports you have commissioned, and any recent enforcement actions or directions from Council relating to heritage matters. The more transparent you are about the planning context, the less room there is for a buyer to claim they were not informed, which reduces the risk of post-contract disputes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the overlay affects your buyer pool</h2>
      <p>The heritage overlay does shape who buys your property and how they approach it. Developer buyers and investors focused on demolition and replacement are typically not your market. The overlay prevents straightforward knock-down-rebuild scenarios, and even where subdivision or significant redevelopment is theoretically possible under the planning scheme, heritage overlays introduce complexity and cost that most developer-oriented buyers will not accept.</p>

      <p>This is not necessarily a disadvantage. Developers and investors have generally not been the dominant buyer type for inner-east character homes in recent years in any case. Your primary buyer pool is owner-occupiers who want a character home, appreciate the heritage aesthetic, and plan to live in the property. For this buyer cohort, the overlay is often a positive attribute rather than a constraint. It provides some protection against the neighbouring properties being demolished and replaced with modern infill, and it preserves the streetscape character that attracted them to the suburb in the first place.</p>

      <p>The overlay does tend to reduce interest from buyers whose primary intent is major renovation or development. If your property has been priced with significant renovation potential or a development premium, you need to be realistic about whether that premium is achievable given the overlay constraints. Your agent should be giving you comparable evidence from similar properties that have sold under the same overlay conditions, not generic suburb-wide data that includes properties without heritage constraints.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting heritage as an asset</h2>
      <p>Properties under heritage overlays in Brisbane's inner east regularly sell at premiums relative to comparable non-overlaid properties, particularly where the home is well-maintained and the heritage character is intact and attractive. The overlay becomes a negative only when it is presented apologetically or when the marketing focuses on what buyers cannot do rather than on the exceptional character, craftsmanship, and lifestyle the property actually offers.</p>

      <p>The marketing should lead with what the property is: an original Queenslander with intact VJ walls and twelve-foot ceilings, a character bungalow with a wrap-around veranda and original leadlight joinery, or a Federation home with a steeply pitched roof and detail work that would cost more to replicate today than the purchase price of the land. These are genuine differentiators in a market where most new stock is built to a formula. Heritage properties attract buyers who know what they are looking for, and those buyers are often well-funded owner-occupiers prepared to pay for quality and authenticity.</p>

      <p>Where owners have already undertaken compliant renovations, including updated kitchens and bathrooms, extensions approved under the heritage code, or energy efficiency improvements that do not compromise character, these become powerful marketing points. The property offers the best of both: original character with contemporary amenity, a combination that is genuinely difficult to find and commands genuine buyer interest.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Checking your overlay status</h2>
      <p>If you are not certain whether your property sits under a heritage overlay, check the Brisbane City Council property mapping tool or the Queensland Globe. Enter your address and look for heritage overlay layers. The overlay may be a local heritage place overlay applying to your specific property, or it may be a character residential zone or precinct overlay applying more broadly to your street or suburb. The implications differ between types, and understanding which applies to your property helps you anticipate buyer questions and set appropriate expectations about what the planning constraints actually mean in practice.</p>

